# .AGENTS

Initial guide for contributors and coding agents in `bem-conecto-nest`.
This is intentionally minimal and focused on core rules.

## 1) Project Snapshot

- Stack: NestJS + TypeScript + Prisma + MySQL + Jest
- Entry module: `src/app/app.module.ts`
- Active feature modules:
  - `UserModule`
  - `ProfessionalModule`
  - `SessionModule`
- Database schema: `prisma/schema.prisma`

## 2) Architecture (Clean-ish by layers)

- `src/domain`
  - Pure business structures: entities, enums, domain DTOs.
- `src/application`
  - Use cases + repository contracts (`*.repository.ts`).
  - Should contain business orchestration logic.
- `src/presentation`
  - HTTP controllers, request adaptation, output mapping.
- `src/infra`
  - Nest modules/wiring + repository implementations (Prisma/InMemory).
  - Prisma service and database adapter code.

Rule of thumb:
- Domain knows nothing.
- Application depends on domain + repository interfaces.
- Presentation adapts HTTP -> application.
- Infra implements interfaces and wires DI.

## 3) Current Conventions To Keep

- Use path alias imports: `@/...`
- One use case per file under `application/*/use-cases`
- Repository token pattern:
  - `export const X_REPOSITORY = Symbol('X_REPOSITORY')`
- Module wiring pattern:
  - Register concrete repository
  - Map token with `useExisting`
  - Build use-cases with `useFactory` + `inject: [TOKEN]`
- Keep controller output mapped (use `*Mapper.toHttp`)
- Soft delete semantics in Prisma queries where applicable:
  - Filter by `deletedAt: null`

## 4) Feature Delivery Checklist (Core)

When adding a new entity operation (`create/read/update/delete`):

1. `application`: create/update use case.
2. `application`: create/update repository contract.
3. `infra/repositories`: implement in-memory repository.
4. `infra/repositories`: implement Prisma repository.
5. `presentation`: create/update DTOs and controller route.
6. `infra/*module.ts`: wire use case and repository token.
7. Add use case unit tests (`*.spec.ts`).
8. Validate with test/build commands.

## 5) Test Pattern

- Prefer unit tests at use-case level.
- For repository behavior in unit tests, use in-memory repositories.
- Minimal expected test set per operation:
  - Success scenario
  - Not found / invalid scenario (when relevant)

## 6) Commands

- Install deps: `yarn install`
- Run unit tests: `yarn test`
- Run a specific test file: `yarn test <path-to-spec>`
- Build: `yarn build`
- Create migration: `yarn prisma migrate dev --name <migration-name>`
- Prisma client generate: `yarn prisma:generate`

## 7) Pragmatic Guardrails

- Do not break existing module/provider wiring style.
- Reuse existing patterns from `User` and `Professional` before introducing new structure.
- Keep DTOs free of system-generated fields (`id`, `createdAt`, `updatedAt`, `deletedAt`) for create flows.
- Convert date-like HTTP values before use-case execution when needed.

## 8) Known Work In Progress

Based on current `TODO.md`:
- `Professional`: delete pending
- `Patients`: CRUD pending
- `Appointments`: CRUD pending
- `Sessions`: read/update/delete pending

---

This file is a baseline. Extend it with domain rules, naming policies, error handling standards, and CI/CD expectations as the codebase matures.
